segments.text: June 22nd, testing one, two, three.
This is June 22nd, and I have the pleasure and honor of chatting with Gary Halter, professor of political science.
Today we're going to be recording his memories of his student years.
Later we'll do his faculty years.
Gary, for someone who might not know you in the future as they listen to this tape or read the transcription,
begin by describing where you grew up, where you went to high school, what your family did.
Describe your life before coming to A&M.
I was born in Amarillo.
My grandparents moved out there and my mother's
family in 1912, I think, and bought land when the XIT Ranch broke up.
And we lived there until I was six years old, and we moved to Oklahoma City for about five years, and then eventually to Wichita Falls.
My dad worked for General Mills, and these were jobs that he was moved to.
And he was a flour miller for General Mills.
And really from, I guess, the sixth grade on, I was around, I only went to the first grade in
Amarillo and then we moved to Oklahoma City.
Moved to Wichita Falls when I was in the sixth grade.
I graduated from high school there and then attended Midwestern University for a year in Wichita Falls before coming to Texas A&M.
You went to Wichita Falls High School?
Yes, Wichita Falls Senior High.
When you got out of high school, what did you think was your goal in terms of major and your profession later?
I wanted to be a veterinarian.
And you went to Midwestern and lived at home?
Yes.
And I worked for a veterinarian there.
How did you come to A&M?
How did you know about it?
What led you to consider coming here?
I was the only vet school in Texas and still is.
And I did get a scholarship from Rotary Club in Wichita Falls, which really made it, I guess, possible for me to come to A&M.
And how much was the scholarship?
It was about $500.
Tuition was $50 a semester and then I had a job and work.
I didn't have a lot of money but I wasn't hard up either.
Books were, you know, nothing like that.
You got here in the fall of what?
Fall of, I guess it would have been 1960.
Had you visited before you came down to enroll?
No.
You had never been to College Station before.
How did you get here that first time?
I came with a friend who had been here the year before, who came his freshman year.
Well, it would have been both freshman years and rode down with him.
What did you bring?

Oh, that they had sent us, the material and stuff that we had to have, the uniform, the number, you know, sort of a list of things that you're expected to have with you when you arrive to survive in the Corps, I guess.
Also, it was in a big trunk.
Was it one of the official footlockers?
Yeah, everybody had to have it.
Where did you get that footlocker?
I don't remember.
I bought it somewhere.
You bought it.
And describe arriving and getting out and finding your dorm and that sort of thing.
Well, I still remember the first time you turned the corner there at Texas Avenue, Highway 6, and what's now University Drive.
I'm not sure what it was then.
You looked over and saw Texas A&M.
You had this water tower and smokestack.
I thought it was a state prison at first.
It really was a bleak-looking place.
I think somewhat disappointing.
I think it was something like, that's it, type deal.
Now the friend you rode with, was he a sophomore?
Yeah.
He had been here the previous year.
Yes, right.
Had he attempted to acquaint you with A&M?
To some degree, yeah.
I think you kind of knew something about what to expect, you know.
Did you have any difficulty in the paperwork of transferring hours and getting admitted and all that?
No, that was, I don't think it's near as complicated as it is today.
Okay, now describe moving into the dorm and getting into an outfit as a sophomore.
Well, I came here expecting to be a freshman, and then I went over to the military science departments.
I'd already been in a year of ROTC at Midwestern, because they also required all, just like A&M did at that time, compulsory two-year ROTC program.
And they did it at Midwestern because they got paid.
So all the guys got to do that.
And they also got down on PE.
I think they had to do so.
And I went over to them and they said, well, you've already had the first two years.
You can't be a freshman in the Corps.
You're going to be a sophomore in the Corps.
And so they send you back and say, go tell your company commander who goes into orbit when he hears this.
God damn, this can't happen.
You can't be a damn sophomore.
Anyway, it was a big confrontation, I presume, between he and the military people, because he came back and said, well, damn it, I don't like it.
Anyway, I think had I known, I probably would have said,
that's okay, I'll stay a freshman.
I don't know what the military people would have said, but it was kind of a case of you weren't accepted by sophomores because you hadn't been through the trial by fire and the freshmen resented it.
But I wasn't smart enough to realize that that was gonna be a problem.
Were you called a frog?
Yeah, oh yeah.
Describe your room and your roommate and that sort of thing.
Well, everything was steel or concrete, I think, in the dorms at that time.
You had steel bunk beds and steel desks.
They did have these big old wooden chairs.
I know Paul Van Riper bought a bunch of them.
He still has them out on his porch in his house in Bryan.
And steel chest of drawers, concrete floor, no curtains, I guess, anything like that.
They were pretty bleak.
And how was your roommate assigned?
They just said, this is your roommate.
A guy by the name of, his nickname was Cocky Anderton.
He was from Bel Air in Houston.
Anderton?
Yeah, Anderton.
And this was by sheer accident?
Yeah.
You didn't know each other?
No, no.
All right, now I know about Fish Old Lady nickname.
Was there a nickname for a sophomore roommate?
No.
Well, I didn't have one, but anyway.
And what outfit?
Company G3.
What was the nickname?
I don't know that it had one.
Which dorm?
16, I believe it was.
In the, quote, new dorm area, new core area.
It was a Northgate dorm area.
Oh, Northgate.
Oh.
Northgate dorms.
It's sort of obscured now because they built those dormitories with the
open-air balconies on them.
It's sort of behind that.
It was the furthest dormitory to University Drive.
Does it have a name now?
I'm sure it does, and I have even seen it, but I don't recall what it is.
No elevator, you know.
We were on the fourth floor, as I remember.
And the first floor was occupied by company E2, which had the dog, the sacred pooch, Reveille, you know.
And there was all of these seniors in the E2 would stand at the bottom of the stairs and every time he would leave for, you know, breakfast, lunch, or dinner and harass you about something.
There was one guy that
He was Hispanic, and his name was Rodriguez.
And he expected us to roll the R when we said Rodriguez.
And we would say, hello, Mr. Rodriguez, and stuff like that.
And of course, he would just go into orbit.
There wasn't much you could do though.
You could act embarrassed and stuff like that.
And he would threaten me what he was going to do.
Anyway, and it was really, I'm trying to think of the guy's name, another guy that did it a lot.
He and some of his friends later owned, in the sense they had a loan on what's now Central Park and College Station.
And when I was mayor, you know, they called and they wanted to talk about whether the city would be interested in buying this land.
And they had a note with the Arnold family, and it was about interest and loan payment at the end.
They'd only been paying interest.
They used it as a party place on weekends.
They could play football games and raise hell.
And so anyway, these guys called one to meet with me about it.
I thought the name sounded familiar, but of course I didn't until I arrived at my office at City Hall.
I hear the guy used to harass me at the front of the stairs.
Anyway, despite that, the city still bought the land from us.
But it turned out, I think, to be a good deal for everybody, for the Arnolds and the city and everything.
How did you, as a transfer, become oriented to all kinds of Aggie traditions and so forth?
Well, very quickly I think was part of it, but not quick enough according to some.
Were you given a guidebook or anything printed?
Well, you had a campusology book, and I think you had to buy those at Lupo's or something.
And you had to be able to answer all of these questions, you know, like where are the pennies in the sidewalk and what's on the back of Lawrence Sullivan Ross' statue and, you know.
All right.
Did a sophomore get quizzed by juniors?
Well, I did because, you know, I was kind of harassed as a freshman even though the, you know, once again it was the ROTC people that said this guy's a sophomore.
It wasn't the Corps that was doing it.
And I was sort of surprised that the current Corps commander that says I'm an advisor to the Corps and I can't really interfere.
I can suggest things.
This is the Marine General.
I can't suggest, I don't like to suggest things.
It certainly wasn't that way when I was there.
Colonel Joe Davis, I think he was the commandant, lived where Vice President Malin Southern lives today in that house.
And, you know, they did a lot of, including surprise inspections in dorms and looking for booze.
And, you know, they even knew where we hid most of it.
You take the medicine cabinet out and hang it on a string behind the wall.
Were you identified in anything on your uniform as a transfer student?
Was there any?
Well, you know, you have different belt buckles that you wear.
A transfer had a different belt buckle?
Right, you had to wear a freshman belt buckle, not a sophomore belt buckle.
It's a smaller Army issue.
Well, all the other brass is the same.
The battalion shields and the cross rifles and the AMC brass, I think, was on the collar.
I think I still have that somewhere.
Were there any, were you assigned some clean up duties and all that other stuff?
I don't think any more than anybody else.
I mean your Saturdays were taken up with drill and other, most Saturdays were, or you know, court reps to football games or something.
All right, academically, how did you get your fall courses?
Did you register after you got here?
Yes.
Describe registration.
Well, I think it was in Sabisa Dining Hall.
And you walked around and picked up slips of paper.
I mean, this is pre-computer card days, I think.
And if there was a card available in the class at the time, you got the class.
Yeah, I don't remember the exact problem, but then you went through a number of stages of harassment and you finally got out of the place with a schedule.
That first semester as you went to class, describe, make any comparison you can think of between the class routines here and what you had known at Midwestern.
Well, you know, just going to class could be an experience, an harassment of various and sundry sorts.
You know, and you had compulsory friendliness.
You had to say howdy to everybody.
And if you knew somebody, you had to say howdy, whatever their name was, you know.
And if you forgot, then you were in trouble, you know.
And anyway, it was, you know, it really wasn't a very pleasant experience.
You had to whip out and introduce yourself to everybody.
And I guess they've stopped all that, I think.
I remember when I came back as a faculty member, I still had freshmen come in and say, howdy, Mr. Holmes, my name is Ray So-and-so, you know.
I always wanted to do the Lloyd Taylor routine.
I heard that he would say, my name's Shit.
I don't know whether that's really true or not.
In class, though, from the faculty's point of view, was there any difference between A&M classes and Midwestern classes in the way the faculty dealt with the students?
No, I don't think so.
They were, you know, they were small classes, just like they were at Midwestern, maybe 20, 25 people at the most, you know.
And what did you get?
Except for chemistry.
Chem 101 was still the way it is.
Who taught that?
I don't remember the guy's name.
I know for one, I think the second chemistry course I had was Rakoff, who was still around as a faculty member when I came back as a faculty member.
Did he have a nickname?
If he did, I don't remember.
I don't remember.
Did you have any impressive faculty that first year?
Some people that you still remember, plus or minus?
Well, I don't recall exactly who I had.
Years kind of, because I was only here two years and they kind of ran together.
There was a guy over in sociology that I know you knew, Harold Brown.

I guess I had never thought about some of the things that he, and he made light of a lot of activity on the Corps, trying to get them to think about, in some cases, the exact stuff that the Bonfire Commission found of tunnel vision and my optic thinking and things of that type.
I don't know.
I was really, I guess I just never encountered that before.
See, he lived across the street from us.
Yes.
And he'd gone to, in Kentucky, oh, boy, the four-year, the small liberal arts college for poor kids.
Oh, Berea, Berea?
Berea, Berea College, yes, he and his wife both.
And the last I knew, he was at the University of Delaware.
Yeah.
Was there for many years.
I had a friend in graduate school at the University of Maryland who had gone to Delaware, you know, and we started talking about faculty members and somehow we both had this guy.
He had one place to meet another.
Yeah, I think he was.
Of course, you had a great deal of influence on me, but that was my second year, which would be my junior year in college.
Right.
That first year, describe your day's routine on a class day.
What time did you get up, what did you do, when, and so forth.
Take through the whole day.
Well, some guy blew a whistle out in the hall, you know, some freshman that was resigned.
By what time?
About 6.30, I think it was.
And he would say, you know, Company G-3, fall out for chow in 30 minutes, or whatever it was, you know.
And he would recite the menu.
The menu is, you know, whatever it was for breakfast.
You had to get up and get dressed, and there was never any time in the morning to shower.
That was something you had to do the night before.
You could have gotten yourself up earlier, but I don't think anybody ever did that at that age.
This was back when sleep was no longer punishment.
So you'd get up and dress in whatever uniform it was.
If it was raining, you'd have your Class C uniform on.
Class A was formal dress, I guess, as I remember.
You put all that stuff on and go fall out.
And maybe the rain with a poncho on and a helmet and stand out in the rain until everybody got assembled.
And they checked to make sure everybody was there.
I don't know what they would have done if you weren't there.
But anyway, they would do that.
And then you'd march over to Sabisa.
dining hall and go in and you set, you know, sort of assigned tables.
And generally there was a senior at the table and maybe some sophomores and freshmen.
And the freshmen, of course, were there to do everything but cut up the seniors' meat, so to speak, in the sense of make sure that everything that he wanted.
They literally didn't do that, but you know what I mean.
That's what it struck me as.
And, you know, you went through that and then you would leave and you didn't march back to the dorms, you went back to the dorms with your classes.
And you had to come back at noon, you know, and make formation again at noon and march over to Savisa and have lunch.
And then, you know, once you got through, you left.
went to afternoon classes, and then you might have some free time in the afternoon to do things.
Of course, there wasn't much to do.
What about intramurals?
Well, there was that, intramural sports in the afternoon, or go to the library and try to hide.
There was an old building called Bagley Hall.
And it was about where the Biological Science Building East is now.
And there were places in there where you could go and study and nobody would bother you.
So we used to sneak over to Bagley Hall and hide among the plants.
There was one room where
and all these plants in there.
Nobody seemed to mind you being in there.
They had lights on when they were growing these plants.
You'd go in there and study.
If you went back to your dorm room, you'd get a rest.
You didn't want to do that.
You had to keep your uniform on all day long and change different uniforms depending on what it was.
There was also, of course, several days a week we had to do Yale practice.
because it was really hard to learn complicated yells like farmer's fight.
Farmers, farmers, you're all right.
You know, I mean, it was terrible.
It took me years to learn.
Anyway, so we went.
There were two or three nights a week you'd go to y'all practice.
Occasionally you'd have silver taps, you know, which everybody came to, I think.
Describe your impression of your first silver taps.
Well, it's pretty awesome, you know, for a young guy, you know.
I mean, there'd be like maybe four buglers up in the,

on the second or third floor, I don't know, I never was in there, but up in the dome of the academic building and they would, the doors in the base are opened and they would play taps and it kind of resonated out of the, out of the dorm, the dome of the, thing and everything of course is, is there no lights, pitch dark, you know, and it's, it's, you know, and everybody's quiet.
It's pretty solemn.
Did, did you all take it seriously?
Oh, yeah.
No pranks or jokes?
No, not at that, or hazing or anything.
You just quietly walked over and stood around the quadrangle in front of the academic nagel in Bolton Hall, and nobody said anything.
I think there was, after taps or before, there were rifle shots.
The Ross Volunteers in front of Sully would stand there and fire, I guess, a 21-gun salute, and then everybody went back to the dorms.
All right, normally on a non-Silver Taps evening, you fell out for chow at what time?
It was early, miners' hours, like 5.30 or so, you know, and maybe 6.
And then, you know, some evenings, too, there were drills, not like, not as condescending as they did every Thursday night, you know, but there would be evening drills sometimes.
practicing marching around Kyle Field, another complicated procedure that, anyway, you'd do those kinds of things, and the band would play, and then he might have you all practice.
And then there was always what we called a quarters, of course, for freshmen and sophomores.
You had to be in your dorm room, at your desk, both feet on the floor, you know, et cetera, and studying from a certain time to a certain time.
During that first semester, did you get the impression that this was a serious place about academics?
No.
It wasn't?
No.
In terms of rigor, compare here with what you had experienced at Midwestern.
I don't know that it was any more difficult, to tell you the truth.
I don't recall that it was.
Did they give you all that old lecture about early on, look to your left, look to your right, because only one of you is going to be here to graduate, that sort of thing?
I'm sure they did.
But I remember very early on, this was, I think, when I was still a freshman, which lasted about a week.
The guy says, why did you come to A&M?
And I said, well, I came to get an education.
And he screamed, he said, that's not the reason you came to A&M.
Why did you come to A&M?
I'm sorry, I thought I came here to get an education.
You came here to be a fightin' Texas Aggie.
And they would go through all that routine.
And I think that was part of the problem I had, you see, is that I never quite accepted that the reason I was here was to become a fightin' Texas Aggie.
I thought I came here to get an education.
But there were great opportunities for not study, one thing the Corps provided you with.
come up with excuses to polish brass and shine shoes and look a lot sharper than everybody else.
Your first football games, what was your impression there?
Oh, that's very exciting.
The whole drama, of course, you've got the home game, you're going to have midnight yell practice beforehand.
I came to call them later the Nuremberg rallies, the torchlight parades to Kyle Field and all of that.
And then of course the marching in around
the track at football games.
Of course, Kyle Field was a fraction of what it is now.
It had that one little upper deck where the press box was.
In fact, that thing is still there under the existing thing.
Now you and your buddies all went to the games.
Oh, yeah, yeah.
There wasn't a question of it.
Did you have any football dates in the fall, that first fall?
Not here at A&M.
I think when we went to TWU or went to, I guess, what game must have been?
The court trip?
Court trip to Dallas or something.
We had the date with some, you know, the arranged dates with women at TWU that was still kind of lingering.
How were those arranged?
Well you just had a mixer thing, you know, and if you found someone you wanted to ask to go to the game with you, you'd ask them.
Now I've heard stories about moose pots, beast buckets, a pot, everybody puts some money in and the guy that gets stuck with the dullest date gets the money.
Did you ever hear any of that?
No, we didn't do that.
I can see that that would even still be done today probably.
Do you remember the first year, was it Fort Worth or Dallas?
No, I don't.
I think that it was Fort Worth.
And how were Aggies treated by the local people on a court trip?
Oh, they were treated very well.
Do you remember how you got up there?
Well, in somebody's car.
Well, I didn't have a car my first year, so I don't know who that was.
Did you ever do any Aggie hitchhiking?
No, I didn't.
Because I think that was pretty well gone by the 60s.
I once, in fact we became pretty good friends, and I'm trying to remember his name, but I was leaving to go to Houston because I had met this girl that was going to the University of St. Thomas.
And I think they came up for the Newman Club, which is the Catholic student organization over at St. Mary's Church.
And I went down to go out with her in Houston.
And I was going out.
There was an Aggie out on the road hitchhiking.
And I picked him up and took him down to Houston.
And he said, well, you know, for giving me a ride, he said, why don't I take you to lunch?
And I said, yeah, great.
So we go to the Houston Country Club.
Now, this guy is a relative.
He was the Mr. Houston for years, the guy that was in the Roosevelt administration.
Jesse Jones?
Yeah, Jesse L. Jones was related to Jesse L. Jones.
At least he claimed he was.
I'm trying to remember his name and I can't.
We also, I think, went to Austin with us one time later on to a game and all.
And he was sort of a secretive guy in some respects, but had some interesting tales of Texas.
While we're on football, the court trip your freshman year, was it to Houston or Austin?
Do you remember?
Yeah, no, I don't.
When you went to Texas games, did those turn out to be special either year?
No, we just got whipped, as we usually did, yeah.
I had a friend from high school, Travis Reagan, who was a football player at A&M.
At that point, one of our stars, I think, and I think it was
It was my junior year that we almost beat them in the Texas game.
It was here at Kyle Field, I do remember that.

And Travis caught a pass and came down in the back of the end zone and of course the referees ruled him out of bounds because Texas was number one in the nation and there wasn't any way that A&M was going to win that game.
That's what everybody concluded.
And there were films that showed she was clearly in bounds and that Texas should have lost the game.
But I'm convinced it was just a foregone conclusion.
And I think Texas came over here kind of unprepared.
A group of people that had done almost nothing all year long.
We had a coach that used to punt on third down.
I forget what that guy's name was, but I always found that.
an odd sort of strategy that if you screwed it up you'd have another chance.
No you wouldn't.
You'd just be screwed up.
Anyway.
What did you and your buddies do those years on Saturday night after a football game, a home football game?
There wasn't much to do, you know.
Come back to the dorm room, maybe try to find some beer somewhere, get an upperclassman to buy some stuff for you.
Where did Aggies drink beer then?
Well, not in the dorms.
That was a real no-no back then.
And, of course, drinking age was 21, as it is now.
And, you know, sometimes you'd drive out on the university farms.
In fact, out in this area where we're sitting, we'd come out here and drink beer.
There used to be a
The place south of here, the Brazos Bowman had an archery range, and the gate was not very secure, so you could go in there and go back in the woods.
They had kind of an area there with a covered thing, and it was for bow hunters.
And that was another place you could go to.
As far as you know, when beer was consumed by those students, perhaps below the age of 21, did a lot of people get drunk?
Oh, I don't think we ever had enough to really get drunk.
I mean, it might be you had maybe two beers for each person about the extent of it.
Was it always pretty well all male?
Oh yeah, yeah.
Well there, you know, there weren't any women around here except maybe a few in Bryan and Colley Station and their parents probably didn't let them date Aggies.
Did you ever go to the Claypits?
I don't know.
I guess not.
I don't know where that is.
Clay pits were down the Welborn Road and then down in somebody's pasture.
And it had been an old digging.
Oh, quarry.
Yeah.
And it was just that stagnant water.
You'd go out there and drink, and they'd skinny dip, apparently.
And I think that was earlier.
Or at Whiskey Bridge.
Did anybody you know ever go to Whiskey Bridge?
Oh, yeah.
In fact, when you turn 21.
You went out there on your birthday, and Alma would give you your choice of, I don't think anything in the house, but you got a choice of something.
Now you say who did?
Alma.
E-L?
No, A-L-M-A, Alma.
Oh, a female.
The woman that ran Whiskey Bridge.
Oh.
